The Water Court of the Great Oasis was the earliest stable hydraulic legal authority of the eastern corridor, predating any royal or dynastic governance at the oasis.
It originated as a council of four sluice masters — one for each of the four cistern chambers of the Great Oasis basin — whose coordinated decisions determined daily water distribution.
The four chambers were designated by cardinal direction and depth: the North Cistern for daily distribution, the East Cistern for drought emergency reserves, the South Cistern for caravan provisioning, and the West Cistern for agricultural irrigation.
The Water Court's authority rested on the Charter of Passage: inscribed on the waystone circle surrounding the oasis, the Charter asserted that any traveler reaching the oasis by recognized route had an absolute right to draw water in the amount specified by their caravan charter.
This right could not be denied by any authority, including the Water Court itself — making the Charter the foundational legal text of oasis civilization and its alteration the most serious crime in Keeper law.
During the Ledger Kingdom period, the Water Court evolved from a four-member cistern council into a complex bureaucracy with hereditary judges, charter clerks, seal inspectors, and water assessors.
The High Water Court served as the supreme arbitration body for water-right disputes across the entire eastern road network.
The oasis Water Court's ledger system — the methodology for tracking water allocation, caravan quotas, and seasonal reserves — was directly adopted by Kowloon's Jade Magistracy for grain and staple management, with the Keeper accounting notation still readable by Jade Clerks today.
The Court fractured after the catastrophic Ninth Meridian Rite destroyed its institutional coherence; three successor factions claim partial authority at the oasis today.
Deltari communities provide hydraulic assessment services to current oasis administrators in exchange for formal recognition of their flow records as legally admissible evidence in water-rights disputes.
The Court's measurement standard — calibrated against the Great Oasis Measuring House's central gnomon stone — remains the reference point for volumetric measurement across the corridor.

