Mafdet's calibration continuity with the Great Oasis Measuring House — the annual exchange of certified reference weights through Sand-Sea Carters' Guild caravans — is the last surviving institutional link between the Water Court's inland measurement system and the Littoral Branch's maritime extension.
A "measure" in Mafdet is the same physical quantity as a "measure" at the Great Oasis, reflecting unbroken calibration continuity since the Keeper era.
Great Oasis witness-seal formulas appear in adapted form in Mafdet's dual-attestation cargo documentation, preserving the Water Court's four-witness format with maritime assessment categories added.
Cargo bearing Great Oasis witness marks receives preferential Mafdet treatment — faster processing, lower insurance rates — because the Water Court's authentication reputation extends across the full corridor.
The Ledger Houses' notation system is descended from the Water Court's Littoral Branch extension, making Mafdet's commercial culture a direct scribal descendant of oasis water-law.

